[4] Costa Rica
Date: Sat 27 Oct 2007
Source: Prensa Latina [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/article.asp?ID=%7B7F47D4DB-94DA-46C1-B973-84B489FB46C1%7D&language=EN>


Costa Rica's Caja de Seguro Social [CCSS; the national social security
system that includes health care. - Mod.TY] has reported since January
[2007] over 24 000 cases of dengue, including 4000 children under 14. The
CCSS says the disease, transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, has
affected over 940 children of 4 years [of age], 1230 between 5-9 years, and
1989 10-14 years.

So far there have been 6 fatalities, including 2 babies less than 12
months, and 250 people contracted the very aggressive and lethal
hemorrhagic strain.

The most affected areas are Guanacaste and Puntarenas on the Pacific coast
and Limon, in the Caribbean. There have also been over 60 cases in the
capital [San Jose].

Specialists claim that a child with dengue is 15 times more prone than an
adult to die.

CCSS Health Development director, Jose Miguel, Rojas announced a sanitation
and prevention drive to eliminate the mosquito breeding sites.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett

[If any Central American country can launch an effective, citizen-based
vector control program, Costa Rica, with its relatively small population,
fairly good infrastructure, and high literacy rate, should be able to. The
2007 rainy season, still going on, has been unusually wet in Costa Rica,
which may be related to the intensity of dengue virus transmission there.

A zoomable health map of Costa Rica can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=10,-84.2,5>. - Mod.TY]

